summary: any tips on caring for togetic?
question: any tips on caring for togetic?
answer:
Though togekisses are entirely herbivorous, togetics need to eat insects as well as plant matter so as to get enough protein to sustain their growth. Togepi get food from their parents, rather than finding it for themselves, so newly evolved togetics aren’t usually very good at catching insects; however, while it won’t hurt your togetic if you feed it protein supplements instead of letting it try to catch insects, it’s usually a good idea to let yours learn to hunt for itself, to foster independence. 

Togetics are easy to house, and are generally very clean; they essentially house-train themselves. They don’t need baths or other grooming beyond occasional nail trimming; some owners also trim their togetics’ wings, but that’s only for people who want to stop their togetics from flying. You will want to watch out for “joy dust”, however– assuming you’re taking care of your togetic and keeping it happy, it will get everywhere. I might recommend investing in a vacuum. 

It may sound trite, but one of the best things a trainer can do to help their togetic is be kind. It’s a bit of a misnomer to say togetics “sense kindness in others’ hearts”– they do have some power to detect a person or pokémon’s intentions, possibly through Aura use, but there’s not really a way to measure “pure-heartedness” in any meaningful way– but it’s undeniable that togetics flourish when their trainers are kind. This is, of course, true for all pokémon, but it’s somewhat more literal for togetics than most others, as togetics will become dispirited and lose energy when not around unkind people. That’s not to say that you must go out of your way to help others at the expense of your own well-being, but simply being kind is good for everyone– the people around you, your togetic, and yourself.

blog.name: pokegodsandmissingno
blog.title: P̵o̵K̸é̴G̸o̸D̷s̸ and Frightful Things to Come?
blog.description: There is a growing desire and expectation of humans here on Earth in making full contact with PoKéMoN who are still unknown. Back in 1995, when I saw my first UPM (Unindexed Pocket Monster), I found out very quickly that other people thought you were totally crazy if you said you saw such things. The world has changed quite a bit since then when I was a child. In fact, in late 1997, a poll taken in Kanto shows that for the first time ever, more than fifty percent of residents now believe in PokéGODS's. Since then, there have been polls that put the figure at over eighty percent or more.
